{
  "texts": [
    "Specific types of securities include stocks, bonds, and investment contracts (Ninth Circuit Jury Instructions Committee 2023).",
    "In the U.S., at the federal level, the offer, sale, and purchase of securities is governed by the following laws:",
    "Securities Act of 1933 (\"Securities Act\"); Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (\"Exchange Act\"); Investment Company Act of 1940; Investment Advisers Act of 1940; Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 (\"Sarbanes-Oxley\"); and Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act of 2010 (\"Dodd Frank\") (Practical Law Securities Litigation & White Collar Crime 2023).",
    "The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) and the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA) are responsible for civil securities law enforcement in the U.S. 5",
    "In addition to violations of the aforementioned regulations, the SEC has the power to charge \"securities fraud based on negligent conduct\" and \"aiding and abetting securities fraud\" (Practical Law Securities Litigation & White Collar Crime 2023)."
  ]
}